<!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In 2019, a group of researchers published a study in the Journal of the American Medical Association. This is not unusual. What was unusual is who the researchers worked for: the Food and Drug Administration. And what they found was that four common chemical sunscreen ingredients — avobenzone, oxybenzone, octocrylene, and ecamsule — were absorbed into the bloodstream after a single day of use at concentrations that exceeded the FDA's own threshold for requiring additional safety studies. The threshold is 0.5 nanograms per milliliter of plasma. The FDA wrote that number itself. It is the line the agency drew in the sand, the concentration below which manufacturers could skip the full toxicology workup. In the 2019 pilot study, all four chemicals crossed it. In the 2020 follow-up — a randomized clinical trial, also conducted by FDA researchers — oxybenzone came in at up to 258 ng/mL. That is roughly 500 times the threshold. The FDA had run its own study, gotten its own answer, and then asked manufacturers to respond with the safety data the rules required. Most of them didn't. Years passed. The products stayed on shelves. The FDA continued advising their use. That is the article.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-threshold" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Number That Was Supposed to Mean Something</h2>
  <p>Regulatory thresholds exist for a reason. They are the institutional equivalent of a written commitment: if a substance reaches this concentration in human blood, the burden of proof shifts. More data is required. The 0.5 ng/mL threshold was designed to operationalize exactly that logic — not to establish that harm occurs above it, but to trigger a requirement for evidence. This is how a responsible regulatory system is supposed to work. You don't wait for proof of harm. You require proof of safety before the harm can accumulate.</p>
  <p>The 2020 JAMA study — expanded to six active ingredients, including homosalate, octisalate, and octinoxate — confirmed what the 2019 pilot suggested. Every tested ingredient exceeded the threshold. Some by orders of magnitude. Oxybenzone, the most widely used organic UV filter in American sunscreens, reached 258 ng/mL. Homosalate reached concentrations that persisted in plasma, with a terminal half-life the researchers measured at up to 21 days. A caveat is worth entering here: terminal half-life in pharmacokinetics refers to the tail end of a drug's elimination curve, not the time the substance is pharmacologically active. "The chemical stays in your body for three weeks" is a punchier sentence than the science fully supports. The honest version is more unsettling in a different way: these are not compounds that clear quickly, and we don't have the long-term data to know what chronic accumulation looks like in people who apply sunscreen daily from childhood into old age.</p>
  <p>The FDA's written rules, under the Sunscreen Drug Products for Over-the-Counter Human Use regulations, required manufacturers to respond to these findings by submitting full nonclinical toxicology packages — the kind of studies that would answer the absorption question with real rigor. The manufacturers were informed. The deadline passed. According to the FDA's own 2021 proposed rule, the agency acknowledged it still lacked sufficient safety data to classify most chemical sunscreen ingredients as Generally Recognized as Safe and Effective. Of 16 active ingredients on the market, only two cleared the bar: zinc oxide and titanium dioxide, both mineral filters.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"We don't know that they're unsafe. We also don't know that they're safe. And by the FDA's own rules, the manufacturers were supposed to resolve that. They haven't."</p></aside>

<section id="what-happened-next" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Happened Next Was Almost Nothing</h2>
  <p>Janet Woodcock, then-director of the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research, offered a statement that managed to be technically accurate and completely unsatisfying in the same breath. The agency was not saying these ingredients were unsafe, she explained. It was saying that the available evidence was insufficient to confirm they were safe — and that more data was needed. Both of those sentences are true. Together, they describe a regulatory agency that has been asking for data since the 1970s, received studies from its own scientists in 2019 and 2020 that dramatically sharpened the question, and is still waiting for the answers it said it needed.</p>
  <p>The manufacturers' non-response is not a mystery. It is a rational business decision. Funding rigorous human toxicology studies is expensive. The results might be inconvenient. And under the current regulatory structure, there is no enforcement mechanism that compels them to act. The FDA can propose rules. It can request data. It cannot, under the existing OTC drug framework, pull an ingredient from the market solely because the manufacturer failed to submit requested safety studies — not without a protracted regulatory process that the agency has declined to initiate.</p>
  <p>Dr. David Strauss, who served as director of the FDA's pharmacology division and was a co-author on both JAMA studies, put it with clinical precision in subsequent commentary: the findings didn't prove harm; they proved that the existing safety determinations were made without the data those determinations required. That is a specific and important distinction that tends to get lost in both the alarmist and the dismissive tellings of this story.</p>
</section>

<section id="structural-trap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Regulatory Trap That Made It Worse</h2>
  <p>The absorption story would be troubling enough on its own. The structural story underneath it is what makes it a systemic failure rather than an isolated lapse.</p>
  <p>The United States regulates sunscreens as over-the-counter drugs. This is not how most of the world does it. In Europe, Japan, and South Korea, sunscreens are classified as cosmetics — subject to different, in many respects faster, pre-market review. The practical consequence of the American approach is that any new active ingredient seeking FDA approval must navigate a drug approval pathway: clinical trials, safety packages, manufacturing standards, efficacy data — the full apparatus. For a sunscreen ingredient, the commercial return on that investment is limited. Generic competitors can formulate with the same ingredient the moment it clears. The incentive to go first and absorb the approval cost is weak.</p>
  <p>The result is a kind of regulatory amber. The U.S. sunscreen market is still largely operating on an ingredient list assembled in the 1970s, while Europe has approved more than a dozen modern UV filters — among them bemotrizinol, bisoctrizole, and drometrizole trisiloxane — with UV absorption profiles that dermatologists consider superior and safety data that regulators in multiple jurisdictions have reviewed and accepted. These ingredients are available in every major European pharmacy. They are not available in the United States because no manufacturer has found it economical to fund the American approval process.</p>
  <p>Congress attempted to address this with the Sunscreen Innovation Act of 2014, which created an expedited review pathway for new ingredients. As of 2025, not one new active ingredient has cleared that pathway. Several applications have been filed. None have been approved. The FDA has cited insufficient data — the same answer it keeps giving, in different contexts, about the same category of product.</p>
  <p>The irony is structural and nearly perfect: the regulatory classification that was designed to ensure rigorous drug-level safety review has instead produced a market where the ingredients that did clear review decades ago face no competitive pressure to be re-examined, and the newer ingredients that might represent genuine improvements can't get through the door. The consumer is left with a choice between ingredients whose safety has not been confirmed by current standards, and ingredients that aren't available at all.</p>
</section>

<section id="conflicts" class="reveal">
  <h2>Follow the Funding, Carefully</h2>
  <p>The Skin Cancer Foundation lists Johnson & Johnson, Neutrogena, L'Oréal, and Procter & Gamble among its corporate supporters. The American Academy of Dermatology receives sponsorship from manufacturers including Beiersdorf and Galderma. These are documented facts, publicly available, and they matter — though not in the way the more tendentious health-scare coverage implies.</p>
  <p>The claim that sunscreen prevents skin cancer is a well-established finding in dermatological research, though some independent critics argue that industry-funded trials overstate benefits for non-melanoma cancers while underplaying alternatives like shade and clothing; still, the evidence from long-term studies like the Nambour Skin Cancer Prevention Trial supports reduced incidence. According to the American Cancer Society's Cancer Facts & Figures 2023, UV radiation causes approximately 97,610 new melanoma diagnoses annually in the United States. Melanoma kills. Daily broad-spectrum sunscreen use reduces the risk of squamous cell carcinoma, reduces actinic keratoses, and is associated with reduced melanoma incidence in long-term trials. Nobody with a serious relationship to the evidence disputes this. The dermatology groups are not wrong to advocate for sun protection. Sunscreen works.</p>
  <p>The conflict of interest question is narrower and more specific: have these organizations, with their manufacturer relationships, advocated as forcefully as the evidence warrants for the regulatory reforms that would bring modern ingredients to market? Have they consistently communicated to the public that the FDA's own scientists found systemic absorption at levels that triggered safety review — and that the required data was never supplied? The answer to both questions appears to be no. The Skin Cancer Foundation's public-facing messaging on sunscreen ingredients has historically emphasized the benefits of use and minimized the uncertainty around absorption data. That is a choice — and it is a choice made by organizations with financial relationships to the manufacturers of the ingredients in question.</p>
  <p>This does not prove the advice is wrong. It raises a reasonable question about which aspects of a complicated picture get emphasized, and which get quietly deferred.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The FDA drew a line. Its own researchers found concentrations 500 times over that line. The manufacturers were asked for more data. They didn't provide it. This is the paper trail."</p></aside>

<section id="endocrine" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Endocrine Question: What the Evidence Actually Shows</h2>
  <p>Oxybenzone has been studied for estrogenic activity since the 1990s. The evidence that it behaves like an estrogen in cell cultures is robust and replicated. The evidence from animal studies adds to the picture: several chemical UV filters, including octinoxate and homosalate, affect estrogenic, androgenic, and thyroid signaling pathways in rodent models at doses that are, in some studies, not dramatically higher than estimated human exposure levels.</p>
  <p>A 2024 review in the Journal of Hazardous Materials surveyed recent research on organic UV filter endocrine activity and concluded that widespread human exposure, combined with demonstrated in vitro and animal-model effects, warranted serious regulatory attention. That is a reasonable scientific conclusion, but the robust animal and in vitro evidence of endocrine disruption at doses close to human exposure levels demands urgent scrutiny—especially since manufacturers dodged the FDA's required studies, leaving us without data to rule out real-world human harm. The honest position, stated without hedging or industry comfort, is: we don't know.</p>
  <p>What we do know is more limited and more verifiable: oxybenzone has been detected in breast milk, amniotic fluid, and urine at population scale. A 2019 study found measurable levels of oxybenzone in 96% of urine samples tested in a Centers for Disease Control and Prevention survey. These are not fringe findings. They are peer-reviewed data from large, well-conducted studies. They document exposure, not harm. But they also document that this is not a theoretical question about whether absorption occurs. It occurs. It occurs in pregnant women. It occurs in their fetuses. Whether that matters clinically — at what level, over what duration, with what biological consequences — is precisely what the FDA's threshold was designed to force manufacturers to answer.</p>
  <p>The industry's response to this framing — "just because a chemical is in your blood doesn't mean it's harmful" — is technically accurate and strategically convenient. It slides past the actual obligation. The threshold was not designed to wait for proof of harm. It was designed to require evidence of safety before harm could accumulate. Those are different standards, and collapsing them is where the accountability gap lives.</p>
</section>

<section id="benzene" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Separate Problem, Worth Keeping Separate</h2>
  <p>In May 2021, the independent laboratory Valisure submitted a citizen petition to the FDA after testing 294 unique batches of sunscreen and after-sun products. It found detectable benzene — a known human carcinogen linked to leukemia — in 27% of them. Some products contained concentrations up to three times the FDA's conditionally restricted limit. The findings triggered widespread voluntary recalls.</p>
  <p>Benzene is not a sunscreen ingredient. It is a manufacturing byproduct — a contaminant that can enter products during the synthesis of certain chemical filters under specific production conditions. Valisure's findings were a quality control and manufacturing oversight failure, not evidence that chemical sunscreen actives are inherently contaminated. The distinction matters, because conflating the two issues — active ingredient absorption and manufacturing contamination — produces a murkier picture than either story deserves on its own.</p>
  <p>What the benzene story adds to this account is a second data point about the same underlying dynamic: a regulatory system with limited resources, weak enforcement teeth, and a demonstrated pattern of learning about problems after the fact. The FDA did not proactively test for benzene in sunscreens. An independent pharmacy did. The FDA did not compel manufacturers to submit long-term absorption safety data. Its own researchers had to publish JAMA papers to make the gap impossible to ignore. In both cases, the agency's posture was reactive rather than anticipatory — and in both cases, the consumer absorbed the risk in the interval between the problem's existence and its public acknowledgment.</p>
</section>

<section id="mineral-filters" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Alternative, With Its Own Complications</h2>
  <p>Zinc oxide and titanium dioxide are the only two active sunscreen ingredients the FDA has classified as Generally Recognized as Safe and Effective. They are physical mineral filters that sit on the skin's surface and scatter UV radiation rather than absorbing it chemically. On the active ingredient question, they are the clear regulatory winner — by default, because they are the only two ingredients that have cleared the current bar.</p>
  <p>The practical picture is messier. Mineral sunscreens, particularly in the high concentrations required for broad-spectrum SPF 50 protection, tend to leave a white cast — a cosmetic limitation that affects compliance, particularly among people with darker skin tones. Manufacturers have addressed this partially with micronized zinc oxide formulations, which are more cosmetically elegant. This introduces a different concern: nanoparticle zinc oxide has its own uncertain safety profile, with ongoing research into dermal penetration and inhalation risk from sprays. The FDA's GRASE determination for zinc oxide predates the widespread use of nanoparticle formulations. Here, too, the data lags the product.</p>
  <p>There is also the reef toxicity question, which is genuine but frequently overstated. Hawaii and several other jurisdictions have banned oxybenzone and octinoxate based on laboratory evidence of coral toxicity. The ecological evidence is real. The policy response is debated among marine scientists, some of whom note that thermal bleaching from ocean warming is a far larger driver of reef decline than sunscreen runoff, and that restricting sunscreen use in high-UV environments carries its own health costs. Good environmental policy and good public health policy do not always point in the same direction, and pretending otherwise is its own form of motivated reasoning.</p>
</section>

<section id="resolution" class="reveal">
  <h2>What a Resolution Would Actually Require</h2>
  <p>The FDA has been requesting safety data on chemical sunscreen ingredients, in various forms, since the 1970s. The formal proposed rule establishing the 0.5 ng/mL threshold and the GRASE classifications was published in 2019. The JAMA studies from 2019 and 2020 were conducted by the FDA's own scientists and published in the world's most prominent medical journal. The agency's 2021 proposed rule stated explicitly that 12 active ingredients could not be classified as safe and effective under current evidence. None of this is obscure. It is part of the public record.</p>
  <p>The manufacturers have two options, and the FDA has articulated both. They can fund and submit the required safety studies — the nonclinical toxicology packages the regulations have required since the threshold was exceeded. Or the FDA, acting under its existing statutory authority, can reclassify ingredients with insufficient data and require their removal from the market until that data is provided. Neither has happened. The FDA has shown no appetite for the enforcement action. The manufacturers have shown no appetite for the studies. The products are on the shelves. The FDA still recommends their use.</p>
  <p>This is not a conspiracy. There is no evidence of corruption or deliberate concealment. What the paper trail shows is something more banal and, in its way, more difficult to fix: a regulatory agency operating under resource constraints, facing a powerful industry with no financial incentive to fund inconvenient research, using a classification framework built for a different era, and defaulting to institutional inertia dressed up as precautionary balance. The manufacturers didn't submit the data because nothing forced them to. The FDA didn't force them because the enforcement pathway is slow and the political cost is high and the public health benefit of continued sunscreen use is genuine and nobody wanted to own the headline.</p>
  <p>The consumer is left with a question that the regulatory system was specifically designed to answer — and didn't. Not because the question was unanswerable. Because answering it was inconvenient for the people best positioned to do so, and because the system gave them the option of not answering. Whether your sunscreen is harming you remains genuinely unknown. Not unknown in the way that most things are unknown — but unknown in the specific, documented, legally-significant way that happens when the right threshold was identified, the threshold was crossed by a factor of 500, the required studies were never submitted, and the agency that wrote the rules decided to keep waiting. The FDA asked the question. It got an alarming preliminary answer. It is still waiting for the full one. So are you.</p>
</section>

